\subsection{Accelerated Sampling and Adaptive Nonlinear Corrections}

In this section, we review recent advances in diffusion-based generative modeling with an emphasis on acceleration strategies and adaptive nonlinear corrections. We first outline the fundamental approaches in score-based diffusion models, then discuss high-order accelerated sampling methods, and finally present adaptive nonlinear correction techniques that improve both convergence and sample fidelity.

\subsubsection{Fundamentals and High-Order Diffusion Approaches}

Score-based generative modeling and diffusion processes have emerged as pivotal tools for image synthesis \cite{li2024accelerating}. Early methods such as DDPM and DDIM reverse the forward diffusion process via iterative updates. Although these approaches successfully capture complex data distributions, the large number of function evaluations required during sampling has motivated the development of acceleration techniques.

Recent studies have incorporated higher-order discretization schemes by leveraging refined Taylor series expansions and insights from high-order ODE solvers (e.g., DPM-Solver-2) to more closely approximate continuous diffusion dynamics. These techniques systematically reduce discretization error and offer provable improvements over baseline samplers \cite{li2024accelerating}.

\subsubsection{Acceleration Techniques in Diffusion Sampling}

To reduce the computational cost of diffusion sampling, several methods have focused on minimizing the number of iterations. Early approaches significantly decreased the number of steps (from \(T\) to much smaller values), albeit sometimes with a trade-off in sample quality. More recent methods exploit high-order approximations to achieve faster convergence rates. For instance, deterministic samplers have been shown to converge at rates of \(O(1/T^2)\) while stochastic samplers can reach \(O(1/T)\) compared to the traditional \(O(1/T)\) and \(O(1/\sqrt{T})\) rates, respectively.

Key aspects of these acceleration techniques include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Higher-Order Discretization:} Refined Taylor series expansions deliver a more accurate approximation of continuous dynamics, thereby reducing discretization error.
    \item \textbf{Training-Free Acceleration:} Several approaches boost the performance of existing diffusion models (e.g., DDIM/DDPM) without requiring additional retraining of the score network \cite{li2024accelerating}.
    \item \textbf{Theoretical Guarantees:} Analyses utilizing tools such as Pinsker's inequality and coupled error bounds on score and Jacobian estimates yield rigorous non-asymptotic convergence guarantees.
\end{itemize}

Table~\ref{tab:acceleration_comparison} summarizes the convergence rates and key advantages of baseline samplers versus accelerated methods that employ high-order approximations.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\newcolumntype{Y}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}X}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l Y l}
\hline
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Convergence Rate} & \textbf{Key Advantages} \\
\hline
DDIM/DDPM & \(O(1/T)\) or \(O(1/\sqrt{T})\) & Baseline simplicity \\
High-Order ODE Solvers & \(O(1/T^2)\) or \(O(1/T)\) & Reduced discretization error \\
ANGAS (Proposed) & Retains accelerated convergence & Adaptive nonlinear correction; training-free \\
\hline
\end{tabularx}
\caption{Comparison of convergence rates and methodological advantages among diffusion samplers.}
\label{tab:acceleration_comparison}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{Adaptive Nonlinear Corrections and Dynamic Step Strategies}

While high-order updates effectively accelerate convergence, they can be sensitive to nonlinear effects and inaccuracies in score estimation, particularly under high-noise conditions. To mitigate these issues, recent approaches introduce nonlinear correction terms inspired by Characteristic Guidance. These methods compute a local residual error at each iteration and adjust the update step to better conform to the underlying Fokker--Planck dynamics.

Adaptive nonlinear correction techniques typically incorporate a fixed-point iteration to approximate and minimize the Fokker--Planck residual. This mechanism serves to:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Mitigate Discretization Error:} By compensating for errors incurred due to linear approximations, the correction term enhances overall accuracy.
    \item \textbf{Enhance Robustness:} Dynamically adjusting the correction strength based on local error estimates ensures that the update remains aligned with the true dynamics without overcorrection.
\end{itemize}

Our proposed Adaptive Nonlinear-Guided Accelerated Sampler (ANGAS) integrates the high-order acceleration strategy with an adaptive nonlinear correction mechanism. This dual approach preserves accelerated convergence rates (e.g., \(O(1/T^2)\) or \(O(1/T)\)) while mitigating nonlinear effects, thereby improving both sample quality and stability \cite{li2024accelerating}.

\subsubsection{Summary and Outlook}

In summary, the evolution of accelerated diffusion samplers has advanced from basic iterative updates to sophisticated methods that unify high-order discretizations with adaptive nonlinear corrections. The literature highlights a trade-off between computational efficiency and fidelity to continuous dynamics. By leveraging advanced numerical integration techniques along with local error monitoring, recent advances provide a foundation for robust sampling methods such as ANGAS, which hold significant promise for efficient and high-quality generative modeling.

