%% ANGAS Method Section

\subsection{Overview of ANGAS}
We introduce the Adaptive Nonlinear-Guided Accelerated Sampler (ANGAS), a training-free, high-order sampling algorithm for score-based diffusion models. ANGAS integrates a high-order update mechanism with an adaptive nonlinear correction, inspired by Characteristic Guidance, to achieve accelerated convergence rates (e.g., $O(1/T^2)$ for deterministic samplers and $O(1/T)$ for stochastic samplers). In addition to rapid convergence, the method actively mitigates errors arising from neglected nonlinear dynamics and inaccuracies in score estimation by dynamically adapting its update rules to better align with the true Fokker--Planck dynamics governing the diffusion process.

\subsection{Key Components and Mathematical Formulation}
ANGAS is composed of three interrelated modules: (i) a high-order update framework, (ii) an adaptive nonlinear correction module, and (iii) a dynamic step adaptation mechanism. The following sections summarize the mathematical formulation for each component.

\subsubsection{High-Order Update Framework}
Let $x_t$ denote the state at time $t$ and let $s(x_t)$ represent the estimated score function. In standard first-order updates, one typically writes
\begin{equation}
x_{t+1}^{\mathrm{base}} = x_t + \Delta x_t, \quad \Delta x_t = \Delta t \cdot s(x_t),
\end{equation}
where $\Delta t$ is the step size. To accelerate convergence, ANGAS scales the update by a factor $\kappa>1$, yielding
\begin{equation}
\Delta x_t^{\mathrm{high}} = \Delta t \cdot \kappa\, s(x_t),
\end{equation}
and the tentative state update becomes
\begin{equation}
x_{t+1} = x_t + \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{high}}. 
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Adaptive Nonlinear Correction}
High-order updates may neglect important nonlinear effects. To compensate, we define an ideal state update
\begin{equation}
\Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}} = \Delta t\, \mathcal{F}(x_t),
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{F}(\cdot)$ characterizes the continuous-time diffusion dynamics. The discrepancy between the tentative update and the ideal dynamics is corrected via a fixed-point formulation:
\begin{equation}
\Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}} = -\gamma \Bigl(x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}}\Bigr),
\end{equation}
with a tunable parameter $\gamma$. The corrected state is then given by
\begin{equation}
x_{t+1}^{\mathrm{corr}} = x_{t+1} + \Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}}.
\end{equation}
A corresponding residual error, which quantifies the deviation from the ideal dynamics, is measured as
\begin{equation}
E(x_{t+1}) = \Vert x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}} \Vert_2.
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Dynamic Step Adaptation}
To balance rapid convergence with stability, ANGAS adjusts the strength of the nonlinear correction based on the local residual error. In particular, if the residual error $E(x_{t+1})$ exceeds a predefined threshold $\tau$, a stronger correction, governed by parameter $\gamma_1$, is applied; otherwise, a milder correction with parameter $\gamma_2$ (where $\gamma_1 > \gamma_2$) is used. Formally,
\begin{equation}
\Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}} = \begin{cases}
  -\gamma_1 \Bigl(x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}}\Bigr), & \text{if } E(x_{t+1}) > \tau, \\
  -\gamma_2 \Bigl(x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}}\Bigr), & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
This dynamic adaptation steers the updated state to more accurately satisfy the Fokker--Planck constraint when deviations are significant.

\subsection{Algorithmic Description}
Algorithm~\ref{alg:angas} presents the complete ANGAS sampling step, combining the high-order update, adaptive nonlinear correction, and dynamic step adaptation into a single procedure.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{ANGAS Sampling Step}
\label{alg:angas}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\State \textbf{Input:} Current state $x_t$, score function $s(\cdot)$, step size $\Delta t$, high-order factor $\kappa$, threshold $\tau$, correction parameters $\gamma_1$, $\gamma_2$
\State Compute high-order update: 
\[ \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{high}} \leftarrow \Delta t \cdot \kappa\, s(x_t) \]
\State Tentative state: 
\[ x_{t+1} \leftarrow x_t + \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{high}} \]
\State Compute approximate ideal update: 
\[ \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}} \leftarrow \Delta t\, \mathcal{F}(x_t) \]
\State Compute residual error: 
\[ E \leftarrow \Vert x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}} \Vert_2 \]
\If{$E > \tau$}
    \State \(\Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}} \leftarrow -\gamma_1 \Bigl(x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}}\Bigr)\)
\Else
    \State \(\Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}} \leftarrow -\gamma_2 \Bigl(x_{t+1} - x_t - \Delta x_t^{\mathrm{ideal}}\Bigr)\)
\EndIf
\State Correct state: 
\[ x_{t+1}^{\mathrm{corr}} \leftarrow x_{t+1} + \Delta x_{\mathrm{corr}} \]
\State \textbf{Output:} $x_{t+1}^{\mathrm{corr}}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsection{Parameter Settings and Implementation Details}
Table~\ref{tab:parameters} summarizes the primary parameters that govern ANGAS.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\newcolumntype{Y}{>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}X}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l Y}
\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Description} \\
\hline
$\Delta t$ & Base step size for updates. \\
$\kappa$ & Scaling factor for the high-order update (typically $\kappa > 1$). \\
$\gamma_1$ & Correction scaling parameter for aggressive correction when $E(x_{t+1}) > \tau$. \\
$\gamma_2$ & Correction scaling parameter for mild correction when $E(x_{t+1}) \leq \tau$ ($\gamma_1 > \gamma_2$). \\
$\tau$ & Threshold for the residual error that triggers aggressive correction. 
\end{tabularx}
\caption{Primary parameters for the ANGAS algorithm.}
\label{tab:parameters}
\end{table}

The parameter values are determined through ablation studies designed to balance accelerated convergence with robustness to discretization errors and score estimation inaccuracies. As ANGAS is training-free, it integrates seamlessly with existing diffusion pipelines without requiring retraining of pretrained score networks.

\subsection{Summary}
In summary, ANGAS refines conventional high-order update methods by incorporating an adaptive nonlinear correction that responds dynamically to local residual errors. This approach ensures that each sampling step adheres more closely to the Fokker--Planck dynamics, thereby achieving faster convergence, improved stability, and reduced artifact formation. The algorithmic steps and parameter settings detailed above form the basis for the experimental evaluations presented in the Results section.

