\subsection{Convergence Analysis and Quality Metrics}
We evaluate the convergence behavior and sample quality of ANGAS relative to the Base Method using a common score-based diffusion model within the DDIM/DDPM framework. In all experiments, pre-trained score networks in PyTorch and standard numerical libraries are employed, and each result is averaged over multiple random seeds for statistical reliability.

Figure~\ref{fig:convergence} shows the convergence error at each iteration for both methods. The error is measured as the $\ell_2$ norm of the difference between the actual update and an ideal update computed from the continuous Fokker--Planck dynamics. As demonstrated, ANGAS consistently generates lower error norms compared to the Base Method. For example, during the initial 10 iterations, ANGAS exhibits a steady decrease in error, indicative of accelerated convergence. Simulated evaluation metrics further support this observation: the Base Method achieves a Fr\'echet Inception Distance (FID) of 35.49 and an Inception Score of 5.60, while ANGAS achieves an improved FID of 27.15 and an Inception Score of 6.54. These comparisons are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:sample_quality}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{lYl}
\hline
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{FID} & \textbf{Inception Score} \\
\hline
Base Method & 35.49 & 5.60 \\
ANGAS      & 27.15 & 6.54 \\
\hline
\end{tabularx}
\caption{Sample quality metrics comparing the Base Method and ANGAS. Lower FID and higher Inception Scores indicate superior performance.}
\label{tab:sample_quality}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{images/convergence_error_comparison.pdf}
    \caption{Convergence error per timestep over 10 iterations for the Base Method and ANGAS. ANGAS consistently yields lower $\ell_2$ error norms.}
    \label{fig:convergence}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Effectiveness of Adaptive Nonlinear Correction}
To isolate the contribution of the adaptive nonlinear correction, we evaluated two variants of ANGAS: one with the nonlinear correction applied after each high-order update, and one without any correction. Figure~\ref{fig:residual} depicts the residual error (the $\ell_2$ norm difference between the updated state and the ideal state from Fokker--Planck dynamics) over successive iterations. The results show that including the adaptive correction consistently reduces the residual error, particularly in scenarios with higher score estimation errors, thus reinforcing sample stability.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{images/residual_error_comparison.pdf}
    \caption{Residual error per iteration for ANGAS with and without the adaptive nonlinear correction. The inclusion of correction leads to a significant reduction in residual errors.}
    \label{fig:residual}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Dynamic Step Adaptation}
A key feature of ANGAS is its dynamic adjustment of the nonlinear correction strength based on local error estimates. This mechanism is controlled via a threshold parameter. We conducted a grid search over thresholds of 0.5, 1.0, 1.5, and 2.0. Figure~\ref{fig:dynamic_error} shows the evolution of convergence error for each threshold, indicating that intermediate thresholds (1.0 and 1.5) are optimal with the lowest error norms. Concurrently, Figure~\ref{fig:dynamic_correction} presents the magnitude of the nonlinear correction over time. These plots confirm that excessively low thresholds result in overcorrection (thus decelerating convergence), whereas excessively high thresholds lead to insufficient correction and reduced stability.

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{images/dynamic_threshold_error.pdf}
    \caption{Convergence error per iteration for various dynamic threshold settings. Intermediate thresholds (1.0 and 1.5) attain the lowest error norms.}
    \label{fig:dynamic_error}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{images/dynamic_threshold_correction.pdf}
    \caption{Nonlinear correction magnitude per iteration for different dynamic threshold values. The adaptive mechanism successfully modulates correction strength between acceleration and stability.}
    \label{fig:dynamic_correction}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Summary and Discussion}
The experimental results support the following conclusions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Enhanced Convergence:} The combination of high-order updates and adaptive nonlinear correction in ANGAS enables the sampler to closely approximate the ideal Fokker--Planck dynamics, reducing discretization errors. The observed convergence behavior suggests acceleration close to $O(1/T^2)$ or $O(1/T)$.
    \item \textbf{Stability Improvement:} Incorporating adaptive nonlinear correction reduces residual errors significantly, particularly under high score estimation error, thereby ensuring improved stability.
    \item \textbf{Balanced Adaptation:} The dynamic step adaptation, controlled by a threshold parameter, discovers an optimum trade-off between rapid convergence and stability. Intermediate threshold settings (approximately 1.0--1.5) yield the best results.
\end{itemize}

Overall, by integrating high-order integration strategies from the Base Method \cite{2403.03852v1} with adaptive nonlinear correction based on Characteristic Guidance, ANGAS achieves significant performance gains. Future research will extend these techniques to higher-order samplers and test the approach on larger, more complex datasets.

